<span id="freeTextContainer15743751988192102455">I really enjoyed Derek Malory&apos;s story. I am getting a bit tired of obnoxious James Malory as I read the series in order. His focus on fighting is tiresome and he comes off as an immature low class street brawler.<br/>Sure there are unrealistic aspects of this story--buying a person means they are a Slave--and no one was appalled at that in the Malory family and demanding that Kelsey be released from bondage immediately. But I have now learned to suspend reality and just enjoy the story&apos;s which are su</span>
  <span id="freeText15743751988192102455" style="display:none">I really enjoyed Derek Malory's story. I am getting a bit tired of obnoxious James Malory as I read the series in order. His focus on fighting is tiresome and he comes off as an immature low class street brawler.<br />Sure there are unrealistic aspects of this story--buying a person means they are a Slave--and no one was appalled at that in the Malory family and demanding that Kelsey be released from bondage immediately. But I have now learned to suspend reality and just enjoy the story's which are sure to have a happy ending.<br />Kelsey and Derek were meant for each other--out of all the couples so far, these two had the most chemistry.<br />I agree with the others the ending was a bit rushed. I don't see why it could not have ended with the wedding; given the circumstances of how the couple met.<br /><br />Surprising how easy it is to snatch a woman (Kelsey) off the streets in the Regency era--this is not the first time it has happened in a Malory novel--every heroine thus far --Roslyn, Reggie, Georgina, and Amy were abducted. </span>
